---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import Search from '../components/Search.svelte';
---

<Base title="Home">
  <!-- ===== HERO ===== -->
  <section class="max-w-4xl mx-auto text-center pt-20 pb-16">
    <p class="text-sm uppercase tracking-[0.3em] text-gold-600 mb-6">Committee Translation AI</p>
    <h1 class="text-5xl md:text-6xl font-semibold text-stone-800 tracking-tight leading-[1.1] mb-6">
      Three AI scholars walk into<br class="hidden md:block" /> a translation committee&hellip;
    </h1>
    <p class="text-xl text-stone-500 max-w-2xl mx-auto leading-relaxed mb-4">
      &hellip;and what they produce is a deeply researched, phrase-by-phrase translation
      informed by the complete indexed corpus of Shoghi Effendi's life work.
      With notes. <em>Really good</em> notes.
    </p>
    <p class="text-base text-stone-400 max-w-xl mx-auto">
      If you remember a certain DOS concordance tool from the early '90s,
      the acronym may ring a bell. That's not an accident.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- ===== THE PROBLEM ===== -->
  <section class="max-w-3xl mx-auto pb-20">
    <div class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-stone-200 p-8 md:p-12 shadow-sm">
      <p class="text-sm uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-gold-600 mb-4">The puzzle</p>
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-stone-800 mb-6">
        One word. Four hours. Zero confidence.
      </h2>
      <p class="text-stone-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        Picture this: you're translating a newly published Tablet of Bah&aacute;'u'll&aacute;h and you hit
        <strong class="font-arabic text-lg" dir="rtl">مظهر ظهور</strong>.
        Roughly: &ldquo;the place where something becomes manifest.&rdquo;
        You could say &ldquo;appearance.&rdquo; You could go theological with &ldquo;theophany.&rdquo;
        You could stare at the ceiling for a while.
      </p>
      <p class="text-stone-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        Shoghi Effendi &mdash; who spent decades turning Bah&aacute;'u'll&aacute;h's Arabic and Persian into
        some of the most luminous English prose of the 20th century &mdash;
        chose <strong>&ldquo;Manifestation.&rdquo;</strong>
        And if you understand <em>why</em>, you're most of the way to understanding
        what makes his translation corpus a masterwork of linguistic architecture.
      </p>
      <p class="text-stone-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        &ldquo;Manifestation&rdquo; carries the philosophical weight of the Latin <em>manifestare</em>
        (to make palpable, to reveal to the senses) <em>and</em> the theological precision of
        something hidden becoming visible. It resonates with Christian vocabulary
        while preserving the Islamic philosophical substrate of the original.
        He used it <em>consistently</em>, across thousands of pages.
      </p>
      <p class="text-stone-700 leading-relaxed font-medium">
        Multiply that decision by tens of thousands of phrases across the
        Kit&aacute;b-i-&Iacute;q&aacute;n, the Kit&aacute;b-i-Aqdas, Gleanings, and dozens of other works &mdash;
        and you get a terminology so coherent that a single English word
        can unlock an entire Arabic concept. <br/>
        <span class="text-gold-700">CTAI gives translators access to that entire system.</span>
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ===== LIVE EXAMPLE: Side-by-side ===== -->
  <section class="max-w-5xl mx-auto pb-20">
    <p class="text-sm uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-gold-600 mb-4 text-center">From the corpus</p>
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-stone-800 mb-2 text-center">
      2,530 paragraphs, indexed and searchable
    </h2>
    <p class="text-stone-400 text-center mb-8 text-sm">Click to explore the full reference page</p>

    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-6">
      <a href="/corpus/the-hidden-words/2/" class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-stone-200 p-8 hover:border-gold-400 transition-all hover:shadow-md block group">
        <p class="text-xs text-stone-400 mb-4">The Hidden Words &middot; Arabic &sect;1</p>
        <p class="font-arabic text-xl leading-loose text-stone-700 mb-6 text-right" dir="rtl">
          يَا ابْنَ الرُّوْحِ<br/>
          فِي أَوَّلِ القَوْلِ امْلِكْ قَلْبًا جَيِّدًا حَسَنًا مُنيرًا لِتَمْلِكَ مُلْكًا دائِمًا باقِيًا أَزَلًا قَدِيمًا
        </p>
        <p class="text-stone-800 leading-relaxed text-lg">
          O SON OF SPIRIT!<br/>
          My first counsel is this: Possess a pure, kindly and radiant heart, that thine may be
          a sovereignty ancient, imperishable and everlasting.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gold-600 text-xs mt-4 opacity-0 group-hover:opacity-100 transition-opacity">View reference page &rarr;</p>
      </a>

      <div class="bg-stone-800 rounded-xl p-8 text-stone-200">
        <p class="text-xs text-gold-400 mb-4">Why this rendering is a masterclass</p>
        <p class="leading-relaxed mb-4 text-stone-300">
          The Arabic <span class="font-arabic text-gold-300" dir="rtl">قَلْبًا جَيِّدًا حَسَنًا مُنيرًا</span>
          is literally &ldquo;a good, beautiful, luminous heart.&rdquo;
          Three physical adjectives.
        </p>
        <p class="leading-relaxed mb-4 text-stone-300">
          Shoghi Effendi transforms these into <strong class="text-white">&ldquo;a pure, kindly and radiant heart&rdquo;</strong>
          &mdash; three <em>spiritual</em> qualities. Same structure, completely different register.
          That's not translation. That's alchemy.
        </p>
        <p class="leading-relaxed text-stone-300">
          And <span class="font-arabic text-gold-300" dir="rtl">مُلْكًا</span> (<em>mulkan</em>)
          becomes <strong class="text-white">&ldquo;sovereignty&rdquo;</strong> &mdash; never &ldquo;kingdom,&rdquo;
          never &ldquo;dominion.&rdquo; Consistent across every work. Every time.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="text-center">
      <a href="/corpus/" class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 text-gold-700 hover:text-gold-900 text-sm font-medium transition-colors">
        Explore the full corpus &rarr;
      </a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ===== HOW IT WORKS: The Committee ===== -->
  <section class="max-w-4xl mx-auto pb-20">
    <p class="text-sm uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-gold-600 mb-4 text-center">How it works</p>
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-semibold text-stone-800 mb-4 text-center">
      Not a chatbot.<br class="hidden md:block" />A consultation.
    </h2>
    <p class="text-stone-500 text-center max-w-2xl mx-auto mb-12">
      Picture three brilliant specialists and one tireless research assistant,
      sitting around a table, going back and forth until they get it right.
      Now picture they have perfect memory.
    </p>

    <!-- Step 1: Research -->
    <div class="relative">
      <div class="absolute left-8 top-0 bottom-0 w-px bg-stone-200 hidden md:block"></div>

      <div class="md:pl-20 mb-12 relative">
        <div class="hidden md:flex absolute left-5 top-1 w-7 h-7 rounded-full bg-gold-100 border-2 border-gold-400 items-center justify-center text-xs font-mono text-gold-700">1</div>
        <div class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-stone-200 p-8">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-stone-800 mb-3">The Research Agent does its homework</h3>
          <p class="text-stone-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
            Before anyone translates a word, the Research Agent analyzes every theologically significant term
            in your source passage. It searches the full indexed corpus &mdash;
            keyword and semantic &mdash; and assembles a <strong>Reference Packet</strong>:
            a dossier of exactly how Shoghi Effendi handled each term, with full surrounding context.
          </p>
          <div class="bg-stone-50 rounded-lg p-5 text-sm">
            <p class="text-stone-500 mb-2">
              Take <strong class="font-arabic" dir="rtl">عرفان</strong> (<em>Irf&aacute;n</em>). The Research Agent finds three distinct renderings:
            </p>
            <ul class="text-stone-600 space-y-1 ml-4">
              <li>&bull; <strong>&ldquo;knowledge&rdquo;</strong> &mdash; general epistemological sense</li>
              <li>&bull; <strong>&ldquo;recognition&rdquo;</strong> &mdash; recognizing the Manifestation of God</li>
              <li>&bull; <strong>&ldquo;true understanding&rdquo;</strong> &mdash; mystical connotation</li>
            </ul>
            <p class="text-stone-400 mt-3 text-xs">
              Same Arabic word, three English renderings. Context is everything.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Step 2: Three Translators -->
      <div class="md:pl-20 mb-12 relative">
        <div class="hidden md:flex absolute left-5 top-1 w-7 h-7 rounded-full bg-gold-100 border-2 border-gold-400 items-center justify-center text-xs font-mono text-gold-700">2</div>
        <div class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-stone-200 p-8">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-stone-800 mb-2">Three translators. Zero groupthink.</h3>
          <p class="text-stone-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            Each agent works <strong>independently</strong> &mdash; no peeking at each other's papers.
            Same source, same research, completely different critical lenses.
          </p>

          <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-3 gap-4">
            <div class="rounded-lg bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 p-5">
              <p class="font-semibold text-stone-800 text-sm mb-1">Dr. Penelope Hamilton</p>
              <p class="text-xs text-amber-700 uppercase tracking-wider mb-3">Literary &amp; Fidelity</p>
              <p class="text-stone-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">
                Keats. Gibbon. The King James Bible.
                She ensures the translation reads like literature, not a gloss &mdash;
                while flagging every deviation from the literal meaning, even the beautiful ones.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="rounded-lg bg-emerald-50 border border-emerald-200 p-5">
              <p class="font-semibold text-stone-800 text-sm mb-1">Prof. Reza Farid</p>
              <p class="text-xs text-emerald-700 uppercase tracking-wider mb-3">Persian &amp; Cultural</p>
              <p class="text-stone-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">
                When your passage echoes H&aacute;fiz or R&uacute;m&iacute;, he's the one who catches it.
                Expert in the layered meanings of Sufi terminology and the specific choices
                Shoghi Effendi made in the Kit&aacute;b-i-&Iacute;q&aacute;n.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="rounded-lg bg-sky-50 border border-sky-200 p-5">
              <p class="font-semibold text-stone-800 text-sm mb-1">Dr. Ahmed Bakri</p>
              <p class="text-xs text-sky-700 uppercase tracking-wider mb-3">Arabic &amp; Theological</p>
              <p class="text-stone-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">
                The Arabic says <span class="font-arabic" dir="rtl">تقلید</span>. A dictionary says &ldquo;imitation.&rdquo;
                Dr. Bakri says <em>&ldquo;blind</em> imitation&rdquo; &mdash; and he can tell you exactly why
                Shoghi Effendi added that adjective.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Step 3: Deliberation -->
      <div class="md:pl-20 mb-12 relative">
        <div class="hidden md:flex absolute left-5 top-1 w-7 h-7 rounded-full bg-gold-100 border-2 border-gold-400 items-center justify-center text-xs font-mono text-gold-700">3</div>
        <div class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-stone-200 p-8">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-stone-800 mb-3">They argue. Then they argue some more.</h3>
          <p class="text-stone-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
            All three renderings are revealed. Each agent critiques the other two on six axes:
            <em>style, historical context, literary allusions, theological terminology, translation precedent,</em>
            and <em>figurative language</em>.
            Agreements get locked in. Disagreements get re-translated. Up to three rounds.
          </p>
          <p class="text-stone-700 leading-relaxed italic border-l-2 border-gold-300 pl-4">
            Truth emerges not from any single perspective but from
            the iterative clash and synthesis of diverse viewpoints offered with detachment.
            <span class="text-stone-400 not-italic text-sm block mt-1">Sound familiar?</span>
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Step 4: Assembly -->
      <div class="md:pl-20 relative">
        <div class="hidden md:flex absolute left-5 top-1 w-7 h-7 rounded-full bg-gold-100 border-2 border-gold-400 items-center justify-center text-xs font-mono text-gold-700">4</div>
        <div class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-stone-200 p-8">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-stone-800 mb-3">From phrases to prose</h3>
          <p class="text-stone-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
            An Assembly Agent weaves the settled phrases into flowing paragraphs.
            A Fidelity Reviewer catches any meaning that drifted in the weaving.
            Every phrase keeps its confidence level &mdash;
            <strong>settled</strong> or <strong>contested</strong> &mdash;
            and the full deliberation notes travel with it.
          </p>
          <p class="text-stone-500 text-sm">
            Those notes? Often more valuable than the translation itself.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ===== CONCRETE EXAMPLE ===== -->
  <section class="max-w-4xl mx-auto pb-20">
    <p class="text-sm uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-gold-600 mb-4 text-center">Live demo</p>
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-stone-800 mb-2 text-center">
      Watch the committee work a single phrase
    </h2>
    <p class="text-stone-400 text-sm text-center mb-8">One phrase. Four perspectives. One convergent result.</p>

    <div class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-stone-200 overflow-hidden shadow-sm">
      <!-- The phrase -->
      <div class="bg-stone-800 px-8 py-6">
        <p class="font-arabic text-2xl text-gold-300 text-center leading-loose" dir="rtl">
          قد اصطفاه الله و جعله مطلعاً لنفسه
        </p>
        <p class="text-stone-400 text-sm text-center mt-2 italic">
          from the Kit&aacute;b-i-&Iacute;q&aacute;n
        </p>
        <p class="text-stone-500 text-xs text-center mt-2">
          Literal: &ldquo;God has chosen him and made him a dawning-place for His Self&rdquo;
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="p-8 space-y-6">
        <!-- Research -->
        <div class="flex gap-4">
          <div class="shrink-0 w-8 h-8 rounded-full bg-stone-100 flex items-center justify-center text-stone-500 text-xs font-mono">R</div>
          <div>
            <p class="text-xs text-stone-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-1">Research Agent</p>
            <p class="text-stone-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">
              <span class="font-arabic" dir="rtl">مطلع</span> appears 23 times in the corpus.
              SE uses solar imagery every time: &ldquo;Dayspring,&rdquo; &ldquo;Day Star,&rdquo; &ldquo;Dawning-place.&rdquo;
              Six instances of &ldquo;Dayspring&rdquo; in Gleanings alone.
              <span class="font-arabic" dir="rtl">اصطفی</span> splits between &ldquo;chosen&rdquo; (casual) and
              &ldquo;singled out&rdquo; (emphatic).
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <hr class="border-stone-100" />

        <!-- Hamilton -->
        <div class="flex gap-4">
          <div class="shrink-0 w-8 h-8 rounded-full bg-amber-100 flex items-center justify-center text-amber-700 text-xs font-bold">H</div>
          <div>
            <p class="text-xs text-amber-600 uppercase tracking-wider mb-1">Dr. Hamilton</p>
            <p class="text-stone-800 leading-relaxed italic">
              &ldquo;God hath chosen Him and made Him the Dawning-place of His Own Self&rdquo;
            </p>
            <p class="text-stone-500 text-sm mt-1">
              Preserves grammatical structure. Every semantic unit accounted for.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Farid -->
        <div class="flex gap-4">
          <div class="shrink-0 w-8 h-8 rounded-full bg-emerald-100 flex items-center justify-center text-emerald-700 text-xs font-bold">F</div>
          <div>
            <p class="text-xs text-emerald-600 uppercase tracking-wider mb-1">Prof. Farid</p>
            <p class="text-stone-800 leading-relaxed italic">
              &ldquo;God hath singled Him out and made Him the Dayspring of His Self&rdquo;
            </p>
            <p class="text-stone-500 text-sm mt-1">
              &ldquo;Singled out&rdquo; has more rhetorical weight. &ldquo;Dayspring&rdquo; is SE's signature word here.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Bakri -->
        <div class="flex gap-4">
          <div class="shrink-0 w-8 h-8 rounded-full bg-sky-100 flex items-center justify-center text-sky-700 text-xs font-bold">B</div>
          <div>
            <p class="text-xs text-sky-600 uppercase tracking-wider mb-1">Dr. Bakri</p>
            <p class="text-stone-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">
              <span class="font-arabic" dir="rtl">نفس</span> (<em>Nafs</em>) here isn't casual &ldquo;self&rdquo; &mdash;
              it's the Divine Essence as manifested in creation. Major doctrinal distinction.
              The emphatic &ldquo;<em>Own</em> Self&rdquo; signals we're not talking about ordinary selfhood.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <hr class="border-stone-100" />

        <!-- Convergence -->
        <div class="bg-gold-50 rounded-lg p-6 border border-gold-200">
          <p class="text-xs text-gold-600 uppercase tracking-wider mb-3">After deliberation</p>
          <p class="text-xl text-stone-800 font-medium leading-relaxed mb-3">
            &ldquo;God hath singled Him out and made Him the Dayspring of His Own Self&rdquo;
          </p>
          <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-3 text-xs">
            <span class="bg-white border border-gold-200 text-gold-800 px-2.5 py-1 rounded-full">&ldquo;Dayspring&rdquo; &mdash; 6 precedents</span>
            <span class="bg-white border border-gold-200 text-gold-800 px-2.5 py-1 rounded-full">&ldquo;Own&rdquo; &mdash; theological precision</span>
            <span class="bg-white border border-gold-200 text-gold-800 px-2.5 py-1 rounded-full">&ldquo;singled out&rdquo; &mdash; rhetorical weight</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ===== THREE VIEWS ===== -->
  <section class="max-w-4xl mx-auto pb-20">
    <p class="text-sm uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-gold-600 mb-4 text-center">Output</p>
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-stone-800 mb-3 text-center">
      One translation, three ways to read it
    </h2>
    <p class="text-stone-500 text-center max-w-2xl mx-auto mb-10">
      Commissioned by institutions, free for everyone.
      The people who most need these texts shouldn't have to pay for them.
    </p>

    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-3 gap-5">
      <div class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-stone-200 p-6 hover:shadow-sm transition-shadow">
        <div class="w-10 h-10 rounded-lg bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 flex items-center justify-center mb-4 text-lg">&#128220;</div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-stone-800 mb-2">Translator's Report</h3>
        <p class="text-stone-500 text-sm leading-relaxed">
          The minutes from a five-hour meeting, compressed into a searchable format.
          Every phrase, every rendering, every critique.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-stone-200 p-6 hover:shadow-sm transition-shadow">
        <div class="w-10 h-10 rounded-lg bg-emerald-50 border border-emerald-200 flex items-center justify-center mb-4 text-lg">&#128269;</div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-stone-800 mb-2">Phrase Study</h3>
        <p class="text-stone-500 text-sm leading-relaxed">
          The spiritual successor to that old DOS concordance &mdash;
          but one that shows you not just <em>what</em> but <em>why</em>.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-stone-200 p-6 hover:shadow-sm transition-shadow">
        <div class="w-10 h-10 rounded-lg bg-sky-50 border border-sky-200 flex items-center justify-center mb-4 text-lg">&#128214;</div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-stone-800 mb-2">Reader's View</h3>
        <p class="text-stone-500 text-sm leading-relaxed">
          Right-to-left Arabic. Left-to-right English. Hover to illuminate.
          The version for people who just want to <em>read</em>.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ===== WHY NOT SINGLE AI ===== -->
  <section class="max-w-3xl mx-auto pb-20">
    <div class="bg-stone-800 rounded-xl p-8 md:p-12 text-stone-200">
      <p class="text-sm uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-gold-400 mb-4">&ldquo;Can't you just ask ChatGPT?&rdquo;</p>
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-white mb-6">Sure. Here's what you'll get:</h2>

      <div class="space-y-6">
        <div>
          <h3 class="text-gold-300 font-semibold mb-1">An average of everything</h3>
          <p class="text-stone-300 leading-relaxed text-sm">
            LLMs have been trained on millions of translations &mdash; every quality level, every tradition,
            every amateur effort. When you ask for a translation, you get the mean.
            Shoghi Effendi's distinctive voice? Drowned out by sheer volume.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3 class="text-gold-300 font-semibold mb-1">Amnesia at scale</h3>
          <p class="text-stone-300 leading-relaxed text-sm">
            The complete corpus spans thousands of pages. No context window can hold it.
            But a search engine can index every word &mdash; and retrieve exactly the precedents
            that matter for <em>your</em> passage. That's the Research Agent's entire job.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3 class="text-gold-300 font-semibold mb-1">One voice, one blind spot</h3>
          <p class="text-stone-300 leading-relaxed text-sm">
            A single prompt produces a single rendering with a single set of biases.
            When Dr. Hamilton and Dr. Bakri disagree about <span class="font-arabic" dir="rtl">نفس</span>,
            that disagreement <em>is the data</em>.
            A single model would silently pick one and move on.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ===== SEARCH ===== -->
  <section class="max-w-3xl mx-auto pb-20">
    <p class="text-sm uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-gold-600 mb-4 text-center">Try it</p>
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-stone-800 mb-3 text-center">
      How did Shoghi Effendi render <em>that</em> word?
    </h2>
    <p class="text-stone-500 text-center mb-8">
      2,530 translation pairs. 7,662 source text segments. Keyword and semantic search.
    </p>

    <Search client:load />
  </section>

  <!-- ===== ECONOMICS ===== -->
  <section class="max-w-3xl mx-auto pb-20">
    <p class="text-sm uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-gold-600 mb-4 text-center">The model</p>
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-stone-800 mb-6 text-center">
      Translate once. Share forever.
    </h2>
    <div class="text-stone-600 leading-relaxed space-y-4">
      <p>
        Good AI translation isn't cheap. The multi-agent deliberation &mdash; independent renderings,
        iterative critique, assembly, fidelity review &mdash; can cost hundreds of dollars for a book-length work.
      </p>
      <p class="text-stone-800 font-medium text-lg">
        But a translation only needs to be done once.
      </p>
      <p>
        Institutions commission and fund the work. The result enters the cache permanently.
        After that? Free for everyone.
        A student in Lagos. A devotional group in Pune. A study circle in Santiago.
        Same high-quality translation, same full annotation, zero cost.
      </p>
      <p class="text-stone-500 text-sm">
        Every institution that commissions a translation contributes to a shared resource
        that grows over time. The people who most need these texts are exactly
        the people who shouldn't have to pay for them.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

